{{short description|An old and stable part of the continental lithosphere in central Tanzania}}
[[Image:Cratons West Gondwana.svg|thumb|right|Approximate location of [[Mesoproterozoic]] (older than 1.3&nbsp;Ga) cratons in South America and Africa.]]
The '''Tanzania Craton''' is an old and stable part of the continental [[lithosphere]] in central [[Tanzania]].
Some of the rocks are over 3 billion years old.{{sfn|Dawson|2008|p=9}}

==Setting==

The Tanzania Craton forms the highest part of the [[East African Plateau]].{{sfn|Dawson|2008|p=2}}
The [[craton]] is surrounded by [[Proterozoic]] mobile belts of various ages and grades of metamorphism.
These include the Ubendian, Usagaran, Karagwe-Ankolean and Bukoban systems. The [[Mozambique Belt]] lies to the east.{{sfn|Geological Framework}}
The craton divides the east and west branches of the [[East African Rift]].{{sfn|Dawson|2008|p=2}}
The southern end of the [[Gregory Rift Valley]] terminates against the craton. The volcanic area of this rift covers the surface interface between the Mozambique [[Orogeny|orogenic fold belt]] and the Tanzania Craton.{{sfn|Dawson|2008|p=9}} A [[superplume]] exists beneath the craton.<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/grl.50694/abstract |title=Mantle transition zone thinning beneath eastern Africa: Evidence for a whole-mantle superplume structure|date=28 July 2013|publisher= |journal=Geophysical Research Letters|volume=40|issue=14|pages=3562–3566 |accessdate=4 August 2017|via=Wiley Online Library|doi=10.1002/grl.50694}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.researchgate.net/figure/276155651_fig8_Figure-13-Simplified-sketch-of-the-Tanzanian-craton-lithosphere-interacting-with-the |title=Figure 13: Simplified sketch of the Tanzanian craton lithosphere...|work=ResearchGate |date=April 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> An indirect effect of rift and plume associated volcanism in the Tanzania Craton is the high levels of soil nutrients in [[Serengeti]] provided by [[volcanic ash]] from [[Ol Doinyo Lengai]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.volcanocafe.org/the-strangest-volcanoes-in-the-world-a-non-official-list/ |title=The Strangest Volcanoes In The World – A Non-Official List|date=28 March 2017|publisher= |accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>

==Composition==

The craton is a composite of several different terranes of Archaean metasediments. The Dodoman is the oldest, and others include the Nyanzian and Kavirondian. Some of the greenstone belts are more than 3 billion years old. They were intruded by granites and [[Migmatite|migmatized]] in different events that date back to 2.9, 2.7, 2.4 and 1.85 billion years ago.{{sfn|Dawson|2008|p=9}}
The [[craton]] mainly consists of [[Archean|Archaean]] [[granitic]] complexes, but also includes rocks from the Dodoma System in the central area, and belts of greenstone to the south and east of [[Lake Victoria]].
Gneisses, schists, quartzites, migmatites, amphibolites and granulite are also found.
There was widespread intrusion of [[kimberlite]]s in the [[Cretaceous]] Period, mostly in the part of the craton that lies south of Lake Victoria.{{sfn|Geological Framework}}
This includes the [[Mwadui]] kimberlite pipe in the center of Tanzania.{{sfn|van Straaten|2009|p=280}}

